{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AwB47bqyAjUJ9uuDnxtKkr","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Cloche Usage\n     2â†’\n     3â†’Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You define a\n     4â†’workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, Cloche copies your project into a Docker\n     5â†’container, runs the workflow steps (agent prompts and shell scripts), and extracts\n     6â†’results to a git branch.\n     7â†’\n     8â†’## Core Concepts\n     9â†’\n    10â†’- **Workflow**: A directed graph of steps connected by named-result wiring.\n    11â†’- **Step**: A unit of work. Type is inferred: `prompt` = agent step, `run` = script step, `workflow_name` = workflow step (host only).\n    12â†’- **Result**: A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. `success`, `fail`, `needs-research`). Steps declare their possible results; the engine follows wiring based on the reported result.\n    13â†’- **Wiring**: Maps `step:result` pairs to the next step. Separate from step definitions.\n    14â†’- **Terminals**: `done` (success) and `abort` (failure) are built-in terminal targets.\n    15â†’\n    16â†’## Workflow DSL\n    17â†’\n    18â†’Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in `.cloche/`. The first step\n    19â†’declared is the entry point. Graphs are validated at parse time (all results wired,\n    20â†’no orphans, entry point exists).\n    21â†’\n    22â†’### Minimal Example\n    23â†’\n    24â†’```\n    25â†’workflow \"develop\" {\n    26â†’  step implement {\n    27â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    28â†’    results = [success, fail]\n    29â†’  }\n    30â†’\n    31â†’  step test {\n    32â†’    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    33â†’    results = [success, fail]\n    34â†’  }\n    35â†’\n    36â†’  implement:success -> test\n    37â†’  implement:fail -> abort\n    38â†’  test:success -> done\n    39â†’  test:fail -> abort\n    40â†’}\n    41â†’```\n    42â†’\n    43â†’### Step Configuration\n    44â†’\n    45â†’| Key | Type | Description |\n    46â†’|-----|------|-------------|\n    47â†’| `prompt` | string or `file(\"path\")` | Prompt template. Makes this an agent step. |\n    48â†’| `run` | string | Shell command. Makes this a script step. |\n    49â†’| `workflow_name` | string | Container workflow to dispatch. Makes this a workflow step (host only). |\n    50â†’| `results` | ident list | Declared result names, e.g. `[success, fail, give-up]`. |\n    51â†’| `max_attempts` | string | Max retries before automatic `give-up` result, e.g. `\"2\"`. |\n    52â†’| `timeout` | string | Step timeout as Go duration, e.g. `\"30m\"`, `\"2h\"`. Default: 30m. |\n    53â†’| `agent_command` | string | Agent binary name(s), comma-separated for fallback chains, e.g. `\"claude,gemini\"`. |\n    54â†’| `agent_args` | string | Override default agent arguments. |\n    55â†’| `feedback` | string | Set to `\"true\"` to include `.cloche/output/*.log` content in the prompt. |\n    56â†’| `prompt_step` | string | For workflow steps: which preceding step's output to use as the prompt. |\n    57â†’\n    58â†’A step must have exactly one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`.\n    59â†’\n    60â†’### The `file()` Function\n    61â†’\n    62â†’`file(\"path\")` reads the file at the given path relative to the working directory\n    63â†’(`/workspace/` in containers) at execution time, not parse time. Use it for prompt\n    64â†’templates:\n    65â†’\n    66â†’```\n    67â†’prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    68â†’```\n    69â†’\n    70â†’### The `container {}` Block\n    71â†’\n    72â†’Can appear at step level or workflow level. Keys are stored with a `container.` prefix.\n    73â†’\n    74â†’**Step level** â€” per-step container config:\n    75â†’```\n    76â†’step code {\n    77â†’  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78â†’  container {\n    79â†’    image         = \"custom-agent:v2\"\n    80â†’    memory        = \"4g\"\n    81â†’    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"api.example.com\"]\n    82â†’  }\n    83â†’  results = [success, fail]\n    84â†’}\n    85â†’```\n    86â†’\n    87â†’**Workflow level** â€” defaults for all steps:\n    88â†’```\n    89â†’workflow \"develop\" {\n    90â†’  container {\n    91â†’    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n    92â†’    image         = \"myregistry/myimage:v2\"\n    93â†’    memory        = \"4g\"\n    94â†’  }\n    95â†’  ...\n    96â†’}\n    97â†’```\n    98â†’\n    99â†’Supported keys: `image`, `memory`, `network_allow`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   100â†’\n   101â†’### The `host {}` Block\n   102â†’\n   103â†’Can appear at workflow level in host workflows (`.cloche/host.cloche`). Keys are stored\n   104â†’with a `host.` prefix. Configures agent defaults for agent steps running on the host.\n   105â†’\n   106â†’```\n   107â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   108â†’  host {\n   109â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   110â†’  }\n   111â†’  ...\n   112â†’}\n   113â†’```\n   114â†’\n   115â†’Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   116â†’`agent_args` config keys override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults.\n   117â†’\n   118â†’### Wiring Syntax\n   119â†’\n   120â†’Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   121â†’\n   122â†’```\n   123â†’implement:success -> test\n   124â†’implement:fail -> abort\n   125â†’test:success -> done\n   126â†’test:fail -> fix\n   127â†’```\n   128â†’\n   129â†’### Wire Output Mappings\n   130â†’\n   131â†’Extract values from a step's JSON output and inject as env vars into the target:\n   132â†’\n   133â†’```\n   134â†’step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135â†’```\n   136â†’\n   137â†’Path expressions:\n   138â†’\n   139â†’| Expression | Meaning |\n   140â†’|---|---|\n   141â†’| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   142â†’| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   143â†’| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   144â†’| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   145â†’| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   146â†’\n   147â†’If the output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the structure. If it's plain\n   148â†’text, only bare `output` works.\n   149â†’\n   150â†’### Retry Loops\n   151â†’\n   152â†’Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   153â†’\n   154â†’```\n   155â†’test:fail -> fix\n   156â†’fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   157â†’fix:fail -> abort\n   158â†’```\n   159â†’\n   160â†’Use `max_attempts` to cap retries. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   161â†’\n   162â†’```\n   163â†’step fix {\n   164â†’  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   165â†’  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   166â†’  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   167â†’}\n   168â†’```\n   169â†’\n   170â†’### Parallel Branches (Fanout)\n   171â†’\n   172â†’Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   173â†’\n   174â†’```\n   175â†’test:success -> lint\n   176â†’test:success -> quality\n   177â†’```\n   178â†’\n   179â†’### Collect (Join)\n   180â†’\n   181â†’Synchronize parallel branches:\n   182â†’\n   183â†’```\n   184â†’collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   185â†’collect any(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   186â†’```\n   187â†’\n   188â†’`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   189â†’\n   190â†’### Comments\n   191â†’\n   192â†’Line comments with `//`:\n   193â†’\n   194â†’```\n   195â†’// This is a comment\n   196â†’implement:success -> test  // inline comment\n   197â†’```\n   198â†’\n   199â†’## Result Protocol\n   200â†’\n   201â†’Steps report results by printing a marker line to stdout:\n   202â†’\n   203â†’```\n   204â†’CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   205â†’```\n   206â†’\n   207â†’For example: `CLOCHE_RESULT:success`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:needs-research`, `CLOCHE_RESULT:give-up`.\n   208â†’\n   209â†’Rules:\n   210â†’- The **last** `CLOCHE_RESULT:` line wins if multiple are printed.\n   211â†’- Marker lines are **stripped** from captured output (not passed to logs or downstream steps).\n   212â†’- The result name must match one of the step's declared `results`.\n   213â†’- For script steps with no marker: exit 0 = `success`, exit non-zero = `fail`.\n   214â†’- For agent steps: if exit non-zero with a marker, the marker result is used. If exit non-zero without a marker, falls back to the next agent in the fallback chain (or returns `fail` if last).\n   215â†’\n   216â†’## Prompt Assembly\n   217â†’\n   218â†’When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from these sections (joined by blank lines):\n   219â†’\n   220â†’1. **Step template**: The step's `prompt` content (inline string or resolved `file(\"path\")`).\n   221â†’2. **User request**: Content of `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt` flag), prefixed with `## User Request`.\n   222â†’3. **Validation output** (opt-in): If `feedback = \"true\"`, reads all `.log` files from `.cloche/output/` and includes them prefixed with `## Validation Output`.\n   223â†’4. **Result selection**: Lists the step's declared results with instructions to print exactly one `CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>` marker.\n   224â†’\n   225â†’The assembled prompt is passed to the agent command via stdin.\n   226â†’\n   227â†’## Agent Command Resolution\n   228â†’\n   229â†’Priority (highest to lowest):\n   230â†’1. Step-level `agent_command`\n   231â†’2. Workflow-level config block (`container { agent_command }` for container workflows, `host { agent_command }` for host workflows)\n   232â†’3. `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable\n   233â†’4. Default: `claude`\n   234â†’\n   235â†’### Fallback Chains\n   236â†’\n   237â†’Comma-separated commands are tried in order:\n   238â†’\n   239â†’```\n   240â†’agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   241â†’```\n   242â†’\n   243â†’- **Command not found / failed to start** â€” try next command\n   244â†’- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** â€” try next command\n   245â†’- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** â€” use that result (no fallback)\n   246â†’- **Exit 0** â€” use result (no fallback)\n   247â†’- **All commands fail to start** â€” step returns an error\n   248â†’- **Last command crashes without marker** â€” step returns `fail`\n   249â†’\n   250â†’Known agents (e.g. `claude`) get default arguments (`-p --output-format stream-json --verbose --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Unknown agents receive the prompt on stdin with no flags. Override with `agent_args`.\n   251â†’\n   252â†’### Agent Setup Guides\n   253â†’\n   254â†’For detailed container setup instructions per agent:\n   255â†’\n   256â†’- [How to set up Claude Code](agent-setup-claude.md) â€” session-based auth, no API key needed\n   257â†’- [How to set up Codex](agent-setup-codex.md) â€” API key configuration\n   258â†’\n   259â†’## Workflow Locations\n   260â†’\n   261â†’**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) run inside Docker\n   262â†’via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type.\n   263â†’\n   264â†’**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) runs on the host machine as the daemon.\n   265â†’Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266â†’dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267â†’execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268â†’fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269â†’\n   270â†’A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271â†’uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272â†’\n   273â†’| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274â†’|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275â†’| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276â†’| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277â†’| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278â†’\n   279â†’Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   280â†’mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   281â†’\n   282â†’### list-tasks Output Format\n   283â†’\n   284â†’The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   285â†’object:\n   286â†’\n   287â†’| Field | Required | Description |\n   288â†’|-------|----------|-------------|\n   289â†’| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   290â†’| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   291â†’| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   292â†’| `description` | no | Full description |\n   293â†’| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   294â†’\n   295â†’The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   296â†’set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   297â†’deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   298â†’\n   299â†’### Host Workflow Example\n   300â†’\n   301â†’A three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   302â†’\n   303â†’```\n   304â†’workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   305â†’  step fetch-tickets {\n   306â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   307â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   308â†’  }\n   309â†’\n   310â†’  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   311â†’  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   312â†’}\n   313â†’\n   314â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   315â†’  host {\n   316â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   317â†’  }\n   318â†’\n   319â†’  step prepare-prompt {\n   320â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   321â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   322â†’  }\n   323â†’\n   324â†’  step develop {\n   325â†’    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   326â†’    results       = [success, fail]\n   327â†’  }\n   328â†’\n   329â†’  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   330â†’  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   331â†’  develop:success        -> done\n   332â†’  develop:fail           -> done\n   333â†’}\n   334â†’\n   335â†’workflow \"finalize\" {\n   336â†’  step push-for-review {\n   337â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   338â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   339â†’  }\n   340â†’\n   341â†’  push-for-review:success -> done\n   342â†’  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   343â†’}\n   344â†’```\n   345â†’\n   346â†’The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   347â†’receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   348â†’workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   349â†’what cleanup to perform.\n   350â†’\n   351â†’### Host Step Environment Variables\n   352â†’\n   353â†’| Variable | Description |\n   354â†’|----------|-------------|\n   355â†’| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   356â†’| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   357â†’| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   358â†’| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   359â†’| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   360â†’| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   361â†’| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   362â†’| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   363â†’\n   364â†’### Container Environment Variables\n   365â†’\n   366â†’| Variable | Description |\n   367â†’|----------|-------------|\n   368â†’| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   369â†’| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   370â†’| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   371â†’| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   372â†’\n   373â†’## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   374â†’\n   375â†’The `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\n   376â†’When you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\n   377â†’generated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\n   378â†’to automate task discovery and cleanup.\n   379â†’\n   380â†’The daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n   381â†’\n   382â†’1. **`list-tasks`** â€” discover available work\n   383â†’2. **`main`** â€” execute the work\n   384â†’3. **`finalize`** â€” clean up after the work completes\n   385â†’\n   386â†’All three workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\n   387â†’required; `list-tasks` and `finalize` are optional.\n   388â†’\n   389â†’### `list-tasks` â€” Discovering Work\n   390â†’\n   391â†’The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   392â†’tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   393â†’\n   394â†’**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   395â†’loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   396â†’\n   397â†’**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   398â†’`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   399â†’\n   400â†’```json\n   401â†’{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   402â†’{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   403â†’{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   404â†’```\n   405â†’\n   406â†’The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   407â†’Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   408â†’5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   409â†’\n   410â†’**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   411â†’\n   412â†’```\n   413â†’workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   414â†’  step fetch-tickets {\n   415â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   416â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   417â†’  }\n   418â†’\n   419â†’  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   420â†’  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   421â†’}\n   422â†’```\n   423â†’\n   424â†’**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode â€” it runs `main`\n   425â†’once without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\n   426â†’runs manually with `cloche run`.\n   427â†’\n   428â†’### `main` â€” Executing Work\n   429â†’\n   430â†’The `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n   431â†’`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n   432â†’\n   433â†’**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\n   434â†’is absent). The daemon sets the `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` environment variable from the\n   435â†’selected task.\n   436â†’\n   437â†’**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\n   438â†’then dispatches a container workflow:\n   439â†’\n   440â†’```\n   441â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   442â†’  host {\n   443â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   444â†’  }\n   445â†’\n   446â†’  step prepare-prompt {\n   447â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   448â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   449â†’  }\n   450â†’\n   451â†’  step develop {\n   452â†’    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   453â†’    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   454â†’    results       = [success, fail]\n   455â†’  }\n   456â†’\n   457â†’  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   458â†’  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   459â†’  develop:success        -> done\n   460â†’  develop:fail           -> done\n   461â†’}\n   462â†’```\n   463â†’\n   464â†’The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\n   465â†’it completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\n   466â†’used as the prompt for the container run.\n   467â†’\n   468â†’You can add steps before or after the container workflow â€” for example, a\n   469â†’`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n   470â†’`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n   471â†’\n   472â†’### `finalize` â€” Post-Run Cleanup\n   473â†’\n   474â†’The `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\n   475â†’of whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n   476â†’\n   477â†’**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\n   478â†’sets two additional environment variables:\n   479â†’\n   480â†’- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` â€” `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n   481â†’- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` â€” the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n   482â†’\n   483â†’**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n   484â†’\n   485â†’```\n   486â†’workflow \"finalize\" {\n   487â†’  step close-task {\n   488â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n   489â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   490â†’  }\n   491â†’\n   492â†’  close-task:success -> done\n   493â†’  close-task:fail    -> done\n   494â†’}\n   495â†’```\n   496â†’\n   497â†’A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly â€”\n   498â†’closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   499â†’Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\n   500â†’finalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n   501â†’\n   502â†’**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   503â†’don't need automated cleanup.\n   504â†’\n   505â†’### Putting It All Together\n   506â†’\n   507â†’The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   508â†’\n   509â†’1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   510â†’2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   511â†’3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   512â†’4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   513â†’5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   514â†’\n   515â†’Start the loop with `cloche loop` and monitor tasks with `cloche tasks`. The\n   516â†’`--max` flag controls how many `main` runs execute concurrently.\n   517â†’\n   518â†’## Complete Example: Container Workflow with Parallel Validation\n   519â†’\n   520â†’```\n   521â†’workflow \"develop\" {\n   522â†’  step implement {\n   523â†’    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n   524â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   525â†’  }\n   526â†’\n   527â†’  step test {\n   528â†’    run = \"bundle exec rake test 2>&1\"\n   529â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   530â†’  }\n   531â†’\n   532â†’  step lint {\n   533â†’    run = \"bundle exec rubocop 2>&1\"\n   534â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   535â†’  }\n   536â†’\n   537â†’  step quality {\n   538â†’    run = \"python3 scripts/quality-check.py 2>&1\"\n   539â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   540â†’  }\n   541â†’\n   542â†’  step fix {\n   543â†’    prompt = file(\"prompts/fix.md\")\n   544â†’    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   545â†’    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   546â†’  }\n   547â†’\n   548â†’  implement:success -> test\n   549â†’  implement:fail -> abort\n   550â†’\n   551â†’  test:success -> lint\n   552â†’  test:success -> quality\n   553â†’  test:fail -> fix\n   554â†’\n   555â†’  lint:fail -> fix\n   556â†’  quality:fail -> fix\n   557â†’  collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   558â†’\n   559â†’  fix:success -> test\n   560â†’  fix:fail -> abort\n   561â†’  fix:give-up -> abort\n   562â†’}\n   563â†’```\n   564â†’\n   565â†’## Container Isolation Model\n   566â†’\n   567â†’- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the project into `/workspace/`. No bind mounts. Override files from `.cloche/overrides/` are applied on top. `.git/` is included.\n   568â†’- **Files out**: On completion, the daemon extracts results via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   569â†’- **Auth files**: `~/.claude/` and `~/.claude.json` are copied into each container at `/home/agent/` for Claude Code session reuse. Copied (not bind-mounted) so each container gets its own isolated copy.\n   570â†’- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   571â†’- **Cleanup**: Containers are removed after successful runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their container.\n   572â†’\n   573â†’Your project directory is never modified by the container.\n   574â†’\n   575â†’## CLI Reference\n   576â†’\n   577â†’Every subcommand supports `--help` (or `-h`) to show detailed usage, flags, and\n   578â†’examples. Use `cloche help <command>` for the same output:\n   579â†’\n   580â†’```\n   581â†’cloche --help              # top-level overview\n   582â†’cloche help run            # detailed help for \"run\"\n   583â†’cloche run --help          # same as above\n   584â†’```\n   585â†’\n   586â†’### `cloche init`\n   587â†’\n   588â†’Scaffold a new Cloche project.\n   589â†’\n   590â†’```\n   591â†’cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   592â†’```\n   593â†’\n   594â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   595â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   596â†’| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   597â†’| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   598â†’\n   599â†’Creates `.cloche/` with workflow file, Dockerfile, `config.toml`, prompt templates,\n   600â†’host workflow (`host.cloche`), and prompt generation script. Skips existing files.\n   601â†’\n   602â†’### `cloche run`\n   603â†’\n   604â†’Launch a workflow run.\n   605â†’\n   606â†’```\n   607â†’cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--title \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   608â†’```\n   609â†’\n   610â†’| Flag | Description |\n   611â†’|------|-------------|\n   612â†’| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   613â†’| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`. |\n   614â†’| `--title \"...\"` | One-line summary for status display. Auto-generated if omitted. |\n   615â†’| `--keep-container` | Keep container on success (failed runs always keep it). |\n   616â†’\n   617â†’Must be run from inside a git repository. The daemon auto-rebuilds the Docker image\n   618â†’when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes.\n   619â†’\n   620â†’### `cloche status`\n   621â†’\n   622â†’```\n   623â†’cloche status <run-id>\n   624â†’```\n   625â†’\n   626â†’Shows run title, type (`host`/`container`), state, active steps, and per-step results.\n   627â†’\n   628â†’### `cloche list`\n   629â†’\n   630â†’```\n   631â†’cloche list [--all]\n   632â†’```\n   633â†’\n   634â†’Lists runs for the current project directory. Pass `--all` to show runs across all projects.\n   635â†’\n   636â†’### `cloche logs`\n   637â†’\n   638â†’```\n   639â†’cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [-f]\n   640â†’```\n   641â†’\n   642â†’| Flag | Description |\n   643â†’|------|-------------|\n   644â†’| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   645â†’| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Log type filter. |\n   646â†’| `-f` | Follow mode: display existing logs then continue streaming new lines as they arrive (like `tail -f`). |\n   647â†’\n   648â†’Without `-f`, displays all logs captured to date and exits (even for active runs). With `-f` on an active run, existing logs are sent first, then new output is streamed in real time via gRPC until the run completes.\n   649â†’\n   650â†’### `cloche poll`\n   651â†’\n   652â†’```\n   653â†’cloche poll <run-id>\n   654â†’```\n   655â†’\n   656â†’Block until the run finishes. Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure.\n   657â†’\n   658â†’### `cloche stop`\n   659â†’\n   660â†’```\n   661â†’cloche stop <run-id>\n   662â†’```\n   663â†’\n   664â†’### `cloche delete`\n   665â†’\n   666â†’```\n   667â†’cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   668â†’```\n   669â†’\n   670â†’Delete a retained Docker container by container ID or run ID.\n   671â†’\n   672â†’### `cloche health`\n   673â†’\n   674â†’```\n   675â†’cloche health\n   676â†’```\n   677â†’\n   678â†’Show per-project pass/fail summary. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP`.\n   679â†’\n   680â†’### `cloche workflow`\n   681â†’\n   682â†’```\n   683â†’cloche workflow [--project <dir>]\n   684â†’cloche workflow <name> [--project <dir>]\n   685â†’```\n   686â†’\n   687â†’List all workflows or render a specific workflow as an ASCII-art graph.\n   688â†’\n   689â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   690â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   691â†’| `--project <dir>`, `-p` | current directory | Project directory to search for workflows. |\n   692â†’\n   693â†’With no arguments, lists all workflows grouped by type (container or host). With a\n   694â†’workflow name, renders the workflow graph showing step boxes, wiring, and result paths.\n   695â†’Wires are colorized: green for `success`, red for `fail`/`failed`,\n   696â†’blue/yellow/orange/magenta for other results. Wires to the same destination are merged\n   697â†’for readability.\n   698â†’\n   699â†’### `cloche get`\n   700â†’\n   701â†’```\n   702â†’cloche get <key>\n   703â†’```\n   704â†’\n   705â†’Get a value from the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   706â†’the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   707â†’the current working directory. Exits 1 if the key is not found.\n   708â†’\n   709â†’### `cloche set`\n   710â†’\n   711â†’```\n   712â†’cloche set <key> <value|->\n   713â†’```\n   714â†’\n   715â†’Set a value in the run context store (`.cloche/<run-id>/context.json`). Requires\n   716â†’the `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` environment variable. Uses `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` if set, otherwise\n   717â†’the current working directory. Creates the file and directories if they don't exist.\n   718â†’Pass `-` as the value to read from stdin (trailing newlines are trimmed).\n   719â†’\n   720â†’### `cloche tasks`\n   721â†’\n   722â†’```\n   723â†’cloche tasks [--project <dir>]\n   724â†’```\n   725â†’\n   726â†’Show the task pipeline and assignment state for an orchestration loop. Displays\n   727â†’upcoming/open tasks, which tasks are assigned to which runs, and auto-assignment\n   728â†’state. Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` (talks to the daemon's web API).\n   729â†’\n   730â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   731â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   732â†’| `--project <dir>` | current directory name | Project to query tasks for. |\n   733â†’\n   734â†’### `cloche loop`\n   735â†’\n   736â†’Start or stop the daemon's orchestration loop. The loop automatically picks up\n   737â†’tasks from the pipeline and runs them.\n   738â†’\n   739â†’```\n   740â†’cloche loop [--max <n>]\n   741â†’cloche loop stop\n   742â†’```\n   743â†’\n   744â†’| Flag | Default | Description |\n   745â†’|------|---------|-------------|\n   746â†’| `--max <n>` | config value | Maximum concurrent runs. Defaults to the value in `.cloche/config.toml`. |\n   747â†’\n   748â†’`cloche loop stop` disables the loop. Running tasks are not cancelled.\n   749â†’\n   750â†’### `cloche shutdown`\n   751â†’\n   752â†’```\n   753â†’cloche shutdown\n   754â†’```\n   755â†’\n   756â†’## Project Layout\n   757â†’\n   758â†’```\n   759â†’my-project/\n   760â†’â”œâ”€â”€ .cloche/\n   761â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ develop.cloche        # Container workflow\n   762â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow\n   763â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Dockerfile            # Container image definition\n   764â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ config.toml           # Project configuration\n   765â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ prompts/              # Prompt templates\n   766â†’â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ implement.md\n   767â†’â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ fix.md\n   768â†’â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ update-docs.md\n   769â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ scripts/              # Host-side scripts\n   770â†’â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/\n   771â†’â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   772â†’â”‚   â””â”€â”€ <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   773â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ prompt.txt        # User prompt\n   774â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ context.json      # Shared key-value store (cloche get/set)\n   775â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ output/\n   776â†’â”‚       â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ full.log      # Unified log\n   777â†’â”‚       â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ test.log      # Per-step script output\n   778â†’â”‚       â”‚   â””â”€â”€ llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation\n   779â†’â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ attempt_count/    # Retry counters for max_attempts\n   780â†’â”‚       â””â”€â”€ history.log       # Step execution log\n   781â†’â”œâ”€â”€ src/                      # Project source (untouched by Cloche)\n   782â†’â””â”€â”€ .git/\n   783â†’```\n   784â†’\n   785â†’## Daemon Configuration\n   786â†’\n   787â†’| Variable | Default | Description |\n   788â†’|----------|---------|-------------|\n   789â†’| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address |\n   790â†’| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   791â†’| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` or `local` (subprocess, for dev only) |\n   792â†’| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   793â†’| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | _(unset)_ | HTTP address for web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   794â†’| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | _(auto)_ | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   795â†’| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | _(unset)_ | Command for LLM calls (evolution, merge conflicts) |\n   796â†’| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | _(unset)_ | Passed into Docker containers |\n   797â†’| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | _(unset)_ | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   798â†’| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | _(unset)_ | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   799â†’\n   800â†’### Client Configuration\n   801â†’\n   802â†’| Variable | Default | Description |\n   803â†’|----------|---------|-------------|\n   804â†’| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon gRPC address |\n   805â†’| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address |\n   806â†’\n   807â†’## Dockerfile Requirements\n   808â†’\n   809â†’The container image must have:\n   810â†’- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   811â†’- `git` installed\n   812â†’- An `agent` user (cloche wraps commands with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   813â†’- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   814â†’- Your project's build dependencies and the agent binary (e.g. `claude`)\n   815â†’\n   816â†’## Build Commands\n   817â†’\n   818â†’```\n   819â†’make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   820â†’make test           # Run all tests\n   821â†’make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   822â†’make lint           # Run go vet\n   823â†’make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   824â†’make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   825â†’make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   826â†’make clean          # Remove bin/\n   827â†’```\n   828â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014nB1uYcqdGQDnmCdayJAtm","session_id":"4d7e8ba7-70ae-45e4-b438-c668f354765a","uuid":"c2e55aee-bcad-4467-98e0-1bc09f6523c0"}
