{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WPVsAmg9fsX6b5b83VpaoE","type":"tool_result","content":"   105â†’\n   106â†’See [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) for the full DSL reference including\n   107â†’parallel branches, collect/join, wire output mappings, host workflows, and\n   108â†’container configuration.\n   109â†’\n   110â†’### 4. Run a workflow\n   111â†’\n   112â†’```\n   113â†’cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add a login page with email/password auth\"\n   114â†’```\n   115â†’\n   116â†’Cloche copies your project into a Docker container, runs the workflow steps, and\n   117â†’extracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` git branch. Monitor progress with:\n   118â†’\n   119â†’```\n   120â†’cloche status <run-id>\n   121â†’cloche logs <run-id> -f\n   122â†’```\n   123â†’\n   124â†’### Let your LLM do the setup\n   125â†’\n   126â†’Your LLM client of choice (Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) can likely handle the\n   127â†’full setup for you. Point it at this README and ask it to initialize Cloche for\n   128â†’your project â€” it can run `cloche init`, tailor the Dockerfile to your stack,\n   129â†’write prompt templates, and wire up a workflow suited to your build and test\n   130â†’pipeline.\n   131â†’\n   132â†’### Further reading\n   133â†’\n   134â†’- [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) â€” full installation options\n   135â†’- [docs/USAGE.md](docs/USAGE.md) â€” CLI reference, project layout, configuration\n   136â†’- [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) â€” workflow DSL syntax and semantics\n   137â†’- [examples/ruby-calculator/](examples/ruby-calculator/) â€” a complete project built by Cloche\n   138â†’\n   139â†’## Containers\n   140â†’\n   141â†’Coding agents are powerful, but running them interactively turns the human into the bottleneck.\n   142â†’\n   143â†’On the otherhand, running them in \"yolo\" mode is wildly risky.\n   144â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4d7e8ba7-70ae-45e4-b438-c668f354765a","uuid":"04f71a63-ea77-4ac5-a892-a40ab09bcf69","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md","content":"\nSee [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) for the full DSL reference including\nparallel branches, collect/join, wire output mappings, host workflows, and\ncontainer configuration.\n\n### 4. Run a workflow\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add a login page with email/password auth\"\n```\n\nCloche copies your project into a Docker container, runs the workflow steps, and\nextracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` git branch. Monitor progress with:\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\ncloche logs <run-id> -f\n```\n\n### Let your LLM do the setup\n\nYour LLM client of choice (Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) can likely handle the\nfull setup for you. Point it at this README and ask it to initialize Cloche for\nyour project â€” it can run `cloche init`, tailor the Dockerfile to your stack,\nwrite prompt templates, and wire up a workflow suited to your build and test\npipeline.\n\n### Further reading\n\n- [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) â€” full installation options\n- [docs/USAGE.md](docs/USAGE.md) â€” CLI reference, project layout, configuration\n- [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) â€” workflow DSL syntax and semantics\n- [examples/ruby-calculator/](examples/ruby-calculator/) â€” a complete project built by Cloche\n\n## Containers\n\nCoding agents are powerful, but running them interactively turns the human into the bottleneck.\n\nOn the otherhand, running them in \"yolo\" mode is wildly risky.\n","numLines":40,"startLine":105,"totalLines":170}}}
